'''Jesse Hall "Pete" Allen''' (May 1, 1868 â€“ April 16, 1946) was a [[professional baseball]] player whose career spanned two seasons, including a part of one in [[Major League Baseball]] with the [[Cleveland Spiders]] (1893). Allen played one game in the majors and went [[hit (baseball)|hitless]] four [[at-bats]]. In that game, Allen played [[catcher]]. He also played in the [[minor league baseball|minor leagues]] with the Binghamton Bingoes (1893) and the [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]] baseball team (1895). During Allen's time in the minors, he played catcher and [[outfielder]]. After his baseball career was over, Allen enrolled in the [[University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine]] where he graduated in 1897. Soon after, Allen began practicing medicine, specializing in [[proctology]].

==Amateur career==
Allen attended [[Amherst College]] from 1892 to 1893.<ref name="amherst">{{cite web|title=Amherst College Lord Jeffs (Amherst, MA)|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/schools/amherstma.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref> Allen became the first attendee of Amherst to play in [[Major League Baseball]] after making his debut in 1893.<ref name=amherst /> After his [[professional baseball]] career was over, Allen  attended the [[University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine]] where he [[coach (baseball)|coached]] the [[Penn Quakers]] baseball team in 1896 and 1897.<ref name="penn bio">{{cite web|title=Penn Biographies: Jesse Hall Allen (Pete) (1868-1946)|url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/people/1800s/allen_jesse_hall.html|work=University of Pennsylvania|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref> Allen was also the [[Penn Quakers men's basketball]] [[coach (basketball)|coach]] in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|title=Professional Baseball Players Who Attended Penn|url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/histy/features/sports/baseball/pros.html|work=University of Pennsylvania|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref>

==Professional career==
Allen began his [[professional baseball]] career in 1893 with the [[minor league baseball|minor league]] Binghamton Bingoes. Allen [[batting average|batted]] .229 with five [[run (baseball)|runs]], 11 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], two [[double (baseball)|doubles]] and one [[triple (baseball)|triple]] in 12 games with the Bingoes. On defense, Allen played [[catcher]] and [[outfielder]]. On August 4, 1893, Allen played his only game in [[Major League Baseball]] with the [[Cleveland Spiders]]. In that game, Allen had no hits in four [[at-bat]]s. On defense he played catcher and made one [[putout]]. In Reed Browning's book ''Cy Young: A Baseball Life'', Browning stated that the Spiders signed Allen out of desperation.<ref>{{cite book|last=Browning|first=Reed|title=Cy Young: A Baseball Life|year=2003|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|isbn=1-55849-398-0|pages=320|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=RfDyEa_4ZfEC&dq=Pete+Allen+baseball&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> In 1895, Allen spent his final season in professional baseball with the minor league [[New Castle, Pennsylvania]] baseball team.

==Later life==
In 1896, Allen enrolled in the [[University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine]].<ref name="penn bio" /> He graduated from that school in 1897.<ref name="penn bio" /> After graduation, Allen started practicing medicine.<ref name="penn bio" /> He specialized in [[proctology]] and was a member of the American Proctology Society, the [[American Medical Association]] and the Philadelphia County Medical Association.<ref name="penn bio" /> Allen wrote many articles for the American Proctology Society.<ref name="penn bio" /> Allen later became the assistant professor of proctology at [[Jefferson Medical College]].<ref name="penn bio" /> Allen served as a staff member for Broad Street Hospital and Methodist Hospital.<ref name=pdf />

==Personal==
Allen was born on May 1, 1868 in [[Columbiana, Ohio]].<ref name="grave">{{cite web|last=Tessein|first=Carik|title=Jesse Hall "Pete" Allen|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSsr=41&GSvcid=123517&GRid=46884898&|work=Find A Grave|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref> He died on April 16, 1946 of [[cerebral vascular disease]] at [[Thomas Jefferson University Hospital]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref name="pdf">{{cite web|title=Deaths|url=http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/reprint/131/9/772.pdf|work=J.A.M.A|publisher=jama.com|accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=grave /> Allen was buried at Media Cemetery in [[Media, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=grave />

